window.GUIDE_TEXTS = {"patient":"Medication Counseling Guide for Hospital Pharmacy\n\nPurpose\n\nThis guide is for short, patient-friendly medication counseling in the hospital.\nIt is meant to help pharmacists and pharmacy interns explain new or changed\nmedications in plain language.\n\nUse this guide to explain:\n- What the medication is for\n- How it helps\n- The most useful side effects to know about\n- What symptoms should be reported right away\n- Simple safety reminders\n- Whether the medication may continue after discharge, if known\n\nThis guide does not replace pharmacist judgment, the medication order, the care\nteam plan, the hospital drug information system, or FDA-approved labeling.\n\nPharmacy interns may share verified information, but they should not answer\nclinical questions on their own. Questions that require judgment or a patient-\nspecific recommendation must be escalated to the supervising pharmacist.\n\n\nTable of Contents\n\n1. Antibiotics\n   Medications: Azithromycin, cefazolin, cefepime, ceftriaxone, doxycycline,\n   ertapenem, piperacillin-tazobactam, vancomycin, linezolid, metronidazole,\n   levofloxacin, ciprofloxacin.\n\n2. Blood Thinners and Antiplatelets\n   Medications: Heparin, enoxaparin, apixaban, rivaroxaban, warfarin, aspirin,\n   clopidogrel, ticagrelor.\n\n3. Diabetes Medications\n   Medications: Insulin glargine, insulin lispro, metformin, empagliflozin,\n   dapagliflozin.\n\n4. Heart Failure, Blood Pressure, and Diuretics\n   Medications: Sacubitril-valsartan, lisinopril, losartan, carvedilol,\n   metoprolol, furosemide, bumetanide, torsemide, spironolactone,\n   nitroglycerin.\n\n5. Breathing Medicines\n   Medications: Albuterol, ipratropium-albuterol, tiotropium,\n   fluticasone-salmeterol, budesonide-formoterol.\n\n6. Transplant and Immune-System Medicines\n   Medications: Tacrolimus, cyclosporine, mycophenolate, sirolimus,\n   everolimus, belatacept, antithymocyte globulin.\n\n7. Infection-Prevention Medicines for Transplant or Low Immunity\n   Medications: Valganciclovir, ganciclovir, sulfamethoxazole-trimethoprim,\n   atovaquone, dapsone, pentamidine, fluconazole, voriconazole, posaconazole.\n\n8. Pain Medicines: Non-Opioid\n   Medications: Acetaminophen, ibuprofen, ketorolac, naproxen, lidocaine\n   patches.\n\n9. Pain Medicines: Opioids\n   Medications: Oxycodone, hydromorphone, morphine, fentanyl,\n   hydrocodone-acetaminophen.\n\n10. Steroids\n    Medications: Prednisone, methylprednisolone, dexamethasone,\n    hydrocortisone.\n\n11. Nausea Medicines\n    Medications: Ondansetron, prochlorperazine, promethazine, metoclopramide.\n\n12. Bowel Medicines\n    Medications: Senna, polyethylene glycol, docusate, bisacodyl, lactulose.\n\n13. Psychiatric, Sleep, and Anxiety Medicines\n    Medications: Sertraline, escitalopram, quetiapine, haloperidol, trazodone,\n    melatonin, lorazepam.\n\n14. Seizure Medicines\n    Medications: Levetiracetam, phenytoin, valproate, lacosamide,\n    carbamazepine, oxcarbazepine, lamotrigine, topiramate, phenobarbital,\n    gabapentin.\n\n15. Electrolytes and Supplements\n    Medications: Potassium, magnesium, phosphate, iron, vitamin D, thiamine,\n    folic acid.\n\n16. Alcohol Withdrawal or Substance-Use Medicines\n    Medications: Lorazepam, diazepam, phenobarbital, thiamine, folic acid,\n    multivitamin, buprenorphine, methadone, naltrexone.\n\n\nQuick Bedside Script\n\nOpening\n\n\"Hi, my name is _____. I am from the pharmacy team. I am here to talk with you\nabout new medications that were started in the hospital. Is now a good time?\"\n\nIf family, visitors, or caregivers are present:\n\n\"I see you have someone with you. Is it okay if we talk about your medications\nwhile they are here?\"\n\nPrivacy reminder:\n- Ask the patient\u0027s permission before discussing medications in front of family,\n  visitors, or caregivers.\n- If the patient wants privacy, pause until privacy is available.\n- If a caregiver is the correct person to teach, follow hospital policy.\n\n\nSimple Medication Counseling Template\n\nUse this for each medication.\n\nMedication name:\n______________________________________________\n\nWhy you are receiving it:\n\"You are receiving this medication for ______________________________.\"\n\nHow it helps:\n\"This medication helps by ______________________________.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n\"Some people may notice ______________________________. This is usually\nmanageable, but please tell your nurse or care team if it bothers you, gets\nworse, or makes you feel unsafe.\"\n[Source: ______________________________]\n\nHow often this happens:\n\"This is considered common / less common / rare but important. Exact chances\ndepend on the exact medication, dose, and your health situation.\"\n\nImportant warning sign:\n\"A less common but important warning sign is ______________________________.\nIf this happens, please tell your nurse or care team right away.\"\n[Source: ______________________________]\n\nMonitoring in the hospital:\n\"While you are here, the team may monitor ______________________________.\"\n\nDischarge or home-medication safety point, only if relevant:\n\"If this medication continues after discharge, the pharmacist or care team may\nreview medicines, over-the-counter products, vitamins, or supplements to avoid\nproblems.\"\n\nDischarge status, if known:\n\"Right now, this medication is expected to be continued / stopped / changed /\nstill being decided at discharge.\"\n\nPatient questions:\n\"What questions do you have?\"\n\nTeach-back:\n\"Just so I know I explained it clearly, can you tell me what this medication is\nfor, or what symptom you should report?\"\n\n\nWhat Pharmacy Interns Should Do\n\nInterns may:\n- Introduce themselves as part of the pharmacy team\n- Confirm whether now is a good time to talk\n- Ask permission before speaking in front of family or visitors\n- Share verified medication name, purpose, common side effects, warning signs,\n  and simple safety points\n- Use teach-back\n- Tell the patient they will review questions with the pharmacist\n\nInterns should escalate before answering questions about:\n- Why a medication was started if the reason is unclear\n- Whether a medication should be stopped, refused, restarted, or changed\n- Dose changes, lab results, kidney or liver function, drug levels, or discharge\n  plans\n- New symptoms that may be side effects\n- Allergic reaction, serious rash, swelling, trouble breathing, severe diarrhea,\n  bleeding, chest pain, fainting, confusion, seizure symptoms, or severe\n  dizziness\n- Drug interactions, duplicate therapy, pregnancy/lactation, transplant\n  medication levels, anticoagulation, insulin changes, opioid safety, or taper\n  plans\n\nSuggested intern wording:\n\n\"That is an important question. I want to make sure you get the correct answer,\nso I am going to review it with the pharmacist.\"\n\n\nPatient-friendly wording:\n\n\"Most people tolerate this medication. Some people may notice _____. Please tell\nyour nurse if it is bothering you or getting worse.\"\n\n\"A less common but more important symptom is _____. If that happens, tell your\nnurse or care team right away.\"\n\nSimple side-effect meaning:\n- Common: happens often enough that it is useful to mention; usually manageable\n- Less common: not expected for most people, but possible\n- Rare but serious: not likely, but important to report right away\n- Important: may need monitoring, treatment, or a dose change\n- Urgent warning sign: tell the nurse or care team right away\n\nFrequency wording for patient counseling:\n- Very common: about 10% or more of patients\n- Common: about 1% to less than 10% of patients\n- Less common: less than 1% of patients, or not expected for most people\n- Rare but serious: uncommon, but important because it may need urgent review\n- Varies: the chance changes a lot by medication, dose, reason for use, kidney\n  or liver function, length of therapy, and other patient factors\n\nFor broad medication groups, use frequency words instead of exact percentages\nunless the exact medication and source are known. For exact numbers, verify with\nDailyMed, the package insert, Lexicomp, Micromedex, or the hospital-approved\ndrug reference.\n\n\nMedication Interaction Safety Checks\n\nIn the hospital, medication interactions are primarily the responsibility of the\npharmacist, provider, and care team. Patients usually do not control which\nmedications are administered while they are admitted.\n\nDo not routinely counsel patients on inpatient drug-drug interactions.\n\nInstead:\n- The pharmacist or intern should screen for interactions before counseling.\n- If an interaction concern is found, escalate it to the supervising pharmacist\n  or care team.\n- Discuss interactions with the patient only if they affect something the\n  patient controls, such as home medications, over-the-counter products,\n  vitamins, supplements, alcohol use, herbal products, or discharge medications.\n\nPatient-friendly wording, only when relevant:\n\n\"While you are in the hospital, the care team checks your medications for\ninteractions. If this medication continues after discharge, pharmacy can review\nwhat to avoid at home.\"\n\n\"Before taking new over-the-counter medicines, vitamins, supplements, or herbal\nproducts after discharge, please check with your pharmacist or care team.\"\n\n\nCommon Medication Groups\n\nUse these as quick patient-friendly prompts. Always confirm the patient-specific\nreason before counseling.\n\nEach medication group includes:\n- Common side effects: symptoms that happen often enough to mention briefly.\n- Less common or rare warning signs: symptoms that are not expected for most\n  patients but should be reported right away because they may need prompt review.\n\nThese sections are a counseling overview, not a full adverse-effect list. For a\nspecific medication, verify exact frequency and warning details with DailyMed,\nthe package insert, Lexicomp, Micromedex, or the hospital-approved drug\nreference.\n\n\n1. Antibiotics\n\nExamples:\nAzithromycin, cefazolin, cefepime, ceftriaxone, doxycycline, ertapenem,\npiperacillin-tazobactam, vancomycin, linezolid, metronidazole, levofloxacin,\nciprofloxacin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This antibiotic is being used to treat or prevent an infection. The plan may\nchange when the team gets more test or culture results.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Nausea, loose stools, mild diarrhea, headache, or rash may happen. These are\n  generally common, but the chance varies by antibiotic and length of treatment.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label; CDC antibiotic side effects]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe, watery, bloody, or persistent diarrhea. This is less common but\n  important. [Source: CDC C. diff]\n- Trouble breathing, swelling, hives, or a severe rash. This is rare but\n  serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- New confusion, seizure-like symptoms, severe dizziness, or unusual weakness\n  with certain antibiotics. This is less common but important. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- New muscle pain or weakness with daptomycin. This is less common but\n  important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Tendon pain, numbness/tingling, mood changes, or severe blood sugar changes\n  with fluoroquinolones such as levofloxacin or ciprofloxacin. These are less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for interactions with vitamins/minerals, anticoagulants, seizure\nmedicines, heart-rhythm medicines, or transplant medicines. Discuss with the\npatient only if it affects discharge or home-medication use.\n\n\n2. Blood Thinners and Antiplatelets\n\nExamples:\nHeparin, enoxaparin, apixaban, rivaroxaban, warfarin, aspirin, clopidogrel,\nticagrelor.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication lowers the chance of harmful blood clots or helps prevent\nplatelets from sticking together. Because it affects bleeding or clotting,\nbleeding is the main safety point.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Bruising or minor bleeding can happen. This is common enough to mention with\n  blood thinners.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Vomit that looks like blood or coffee grounds. This is less common but\n  serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Black or bloody stool. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Blood in urine. This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Severe headache, new weakness, confusion, fall, or head injury. This is less\n  common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Bleeding that will not stop. This is less common but serious. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for duplicate anticoagulants/antiplatelets, NSAIDs, procedures, renal\nfunction, and bleeding risk. Discuss OTC pain relievers only if relevant to\ndischarge or home use.\n\n\n3. Diabetes Medications\n\nExamples:\nInsulin glargine, rapid-acting insulin such as insulin lispro, metformin,\nempagliflozin, dapagliflozin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps manage blood sugar. In the hospital, blood sugar can\nchange because of illness, meals, tube feeds, steroids, surgery, or kidney\nfunction.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Insulin can cause low blood sugar. This is common and clinically important.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label; MedlinePlus hypoglycemia]\n- Metformin can cause stomach upset or diarrhea. This is common, especially\n  when starting or increasing the dose. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- SGLT2 medicines such as empagliflozin or dapagliflozin can increase urination\n  or genital/urinary infection risk. These are common enough to mention.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Shaking, sweating, confusion, weakness, fast heartbeat, or feeling like blood\n  sugar is low. Low blood sugar is common with insulin and should be reported\n  early. [Source: MedlinePlus hypoglycemia]\n- Vomiting, severe weakness, fast breathing, or feeling very ill with diabetes\n  medicines. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Pain, redness, swelling, fever, or serious infection symptoms in the genital\n  area with SGLT2 medicines. This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n\nPatient-controlled safety point:\n\"Please tell staff if you miss a meal, cannot eat, vomit, or feel symptoms of\nlow blood sugar.\"\n\n\n4. Heart Failure, Blood Pressure, and Diuretics\n\nExamples:\nSacubitril-valsartan, lisinopril, losartan, carvedilol, metoprolol, furosemide,\nbumetanide, torsemide, spironolactone, nitroglycerin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps with blood pressure, heart rate, fluid, or heart\nprotection.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Dizziness, tiredness, increased urination, or lower blood pressure can happen.\n  These are common enough to mention, especially when doses are started or\n  changed. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Fainting, severe dizziness, chest pain, or trouble breathing. This is less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Very slow heart rate or feeling like you may pass out with beta-blockers.\n  This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Muscle weakness, severe cramps, or heart-rhythm symptoms that may suggest\n  electrolyte changes. This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Swelling of the face, lips, tongue, or throat with ACE inhibitors such as\n  lisinopril. This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for potassium, kidney function, duplicate blood pressure therapy, and\nmedicines that may increase dizziness or low blood pressure. Routine patient\ncounseling should focus on symptoms to report.\n\n\n5. Breathing Medicines\n\nExamples:\nAlbuterol, ipratropium-albuterol, tiotropium, fluticasone-salmeterol,\nbudesonide-formoterol.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps your breathing. Some inhalers or breathing treatments\nwork quickly, and others are maintenance medicines.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Shakiness or fast heartbeat can be common with rescue breathing medicines such\n  as albuterol. Dry mouth, hoarseness, or throat irritation can also happen and\n  frequency varies by inhaler. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Chest pain, severe fast heartbeat, or feeling faint. This is less common but\n  important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Breathing that gets worse right after a treatment. This is rare but serious.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Fever, worsening cough, or symptoms of pneumonia with inhaled steroid\n  combinations. This is less common but important, especially in COPD. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMedication history point:\n\"If you use inhalers at home, tell the team which ones you use.\"\n\nPractical tip:\n\"If this inhaler contains a steroid and you continue it after discharge, rinse\nyour mouth after using it to lower the chance of thrush.\" [Source: DailyMed FDA\nlabel]\n\n\n6. Transplant and Immune-System Medicines\n\nExamples:\nTacrolimus, cyclosporine, mycophenolate, sirolimus, everolimus, belatacept,\nantithymocyte globulin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication lowers immune activity to help protect your transplant or treat\nan immune-related problem.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Tremor, headache, diarrhea, nausea, infection risk, blood pressure changes,\n  kidney lab changes, or blood count changes may happen. These are common to\n  very common for some transplant medicines, but the exact chance varies by\n  medicine and transplant regimen. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Fever, chills, sore throat, or other infection symptoms. Infection risk is\n  common and can become serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe diarrhea, vomiting, or inability to keep medicines down. This is less\n  common but important because missed doses can matter. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Severe tremor, confusion, seizure symptoms, or major change in alertness.\n  This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Very low urine output, major swelling, or concern for kidney problems. This is\n  less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nTransplant medicines have many clinically important interactions. Screen with\nthe pharmacist/transplant team. Discuss with the patient only for discharge,\nhome medicines, supplements, herbal products, or missed-dose instructions.\n\n\n7. Infection-Prevention Medicines for Transplant or Low Immunity\n\nExamples:\nValganciclovir, ganciclovir, sulfamethoxazole-trimethoprim, atovaquone,\ndapsone, pentamidine, fluconazole, voriconazole, posaconazole.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps prevent or treat infections while your immune system is\nweaker.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Nausea, diarrhea, headache, and rash are common enough to mention for many of\n  these medicines. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Blood count changes, kidney/liver lab changes, or electrolyte changes vary by\n  medicine and are often found by monitoring labs. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Fever, chills, sore throat, unusual bruising, or signs of low blood counts.\n  This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe rash or trouble breathing. This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed\n  FDA label]\n- Yellow skin/eyes, dark urine, severe stomach pain, or concern for liver\n  problems. This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe weakness, shortness of breath, blue/gray lips, or dark urine with\n  dapsone. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen antifungals and antivirals for interactions with transplant medicines,\nanticoagulants, statins, seizure medicines, and heart-rhythm medicines. Discuss\nwith the patient only if relevant to discharge or home use.\n\n\n8. Pain Medicines: Non-Opioid\n\nExamples:\nAcetaminophen, ibuprofen, ketorolac, naproxen, lidocaine patches.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps with pain or fever.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Acetaminophen is usually well tolerated at safe doses; side effects are\n  uncommon when total daily dose is safe. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- NSAIDs such as ibuprofen, ketorolac, and naproxen can irritate the stomach and\n  affect bleeding risk, blood pressure, or kidneys. These risks vary by dose,\n  length of use, kidney function, bleeding risk, and other conditions. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe stomach pain, black/bloody stool, vomiting blood, or unusual bleeding\n  with NSAIDs. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Yellow skin/eyes, dark urine, or severe nausea after too much acetaminophen.\n  This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen NSAIDs and acetaminophen for bleeding, kidney, liver, heart failure, and\nduplicate-therapy risks. Discuss OTC pain medicine only if discharge or home use\nis relevant.\n\n\n9. Pain Medicines: Opioids\n\nExamples:\nOxycodone, hydromorphone, morphine, fentanyl, hydrocodone-acetaminophen.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication treats moderate to severe pain. In the hospital, nurses give\nit based on the care team\u0027s orders and safety checks.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, constipation, nausea, and dizziness are common with opioids. Fall\n  risk is clinically important, especially in the hospital. [Source: FDA opioid\n  safety communication; DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Very slow or difficult breathing. This is less common but serious. [Source:\n  FDA opioid safety communication]\n- Extreme sleepiness, confusion, or hard to wake up. This is less common but\n  serious. [Source: FDA opioid safety communication]\n- Severe dizziness or a fall. This is less common but important. [Source: FDA\n  opioid safety communication]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for benzodiazepines, gabapentin/pregabalin, sleep medicines, alcohol use,\nand other sedating medicines. For inpatient counseling, focus on reporting\nexcessive sleepiness or breathing problems.\n\n\n10. Steroids\n\nExamples:\nPrednisone, methylprednisolone, dexamethasone, hydrocortisone.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"Steroids reduce inflammation or help with conditions such as breathing\nproblems, allergic reactions, autoimmune conditions, or adrenal problems.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Increased appetite, trouble sleeping, mood changes, fluid retention, and\n  higher blood sugar are common enough to mention, especially with higher doses\n  or longer courses. [Source: DailyMed FDA label; MedlinePlus prednisone]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe mood changes, confusion, signs of infection, black/bloody stool, or\n  very high blood sugar symptoms. These are less common but important. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label; MedlinePlus prednisone]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for diabetes therapy changes, NSAIDs, anticoagulants/antiplatelets, and\ninfection risk. Discuss discharge taper or home OTC use only if relevant.\n\n\n11. Nausea Medicines\n\nExamples:\nOndansetron, prochlorperazine, promethazine, metoclopramide.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps prevent or treat nausea and vomiting.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, constipation, or headache may happen. These are common\n  enough to mention, but the chance varies by nausea medicine. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Fainting, racing heartbeat, severe dizziness, or heart-rhythm symptoms. This\n  is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Restlessness, tremor, stiffness, or unusual movements with metoclopramide or\n  similar medicines. This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for sedation, QT prolongation, dopamine-blocking combinations, and\nserotonergic combinations. Patient counseling should focus on symptoms to report.\n\n\n12. Bowel Medicines\n\nExamples:\nSenna, polyethylene glycol, docusate, bisacodyl, lactulose.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps with constipation or helps meet bowel movement goals.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Cramping, gas, loose stools, or diarrhea are common enough to mention with\n  bowel medicines. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe diarrhea, severe stomach pain, dehydration symptoms, or no bowel\n  movement when the care team expected one. This is less common but important.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPatient-controlled safety point:\n\"Please tell staff about diarrhea, constipation, or missed bowel movements so\nthe plan can be adjusted.\"\n\n\n13. Psychiatric, Sleep, and Anxiety Medicines\n\nExamples:\nSertraline, escitalopram, quetiapine, haloperidol, trazodone, melatonin,\nlorazepam.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication may help with mood, anxiety, sleep, agitation, delirium, or\nanother mental health or neurologic symptom.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, dry mouth, or nausea are common enough to mention for\n  many of these medicines. Fall risk is clinically important in the hospital.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe sleepiness, confusion, slowed breathing, or falls with sedating\n  medicines. This is less common but serious. [Source: FDA opioid/benzodiazepine\n  safety communication; DailyMed FDA label]\n- New suicidal thoughts, severe mood changes, severe restlessness, stiffness, or\n  abnormal movements. These are less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for opioids, benzodiazepines, sleep medicines, alcohol use, QT-risk\nmedicines, serotonergic combinations, and duplicate sedating therapy. Patient\ncounseling should focus on sedation, falls, breathing, and behavior changes.\n\n\n14. Seizure Medicines\n\nExamples:\nLevetiracetam, phenytoin, valproate, lacosamide, carbamazepine, oxcarbazepine,\nlamotrigine, topiramate, phenobarbital, gabapentin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps prevent or treat seizures, or it may be used for another\ncondition such as nerve pain, mood, migraine prevention, or withdrawal. We\nconfirm the reason from your chart.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, trouble walking, nausea, headache, or mood changes may\n  happen depending on the medication. Many seizure medicines commonly cause\n  sleepiness or dizziness, especially when starting or changing doses. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe rash, blistering rash, mouth sores, or skin peeling with medicines such\n  as lamotrigine or carbamazepine. This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed\n  FDA label]\n- Severe confusion, unsteady walking, slurred speech, abnormal eye movements, or\n  extreme sleepiness. This is less common but important and may suggest too much\n  medication effect. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- New or worsening depression, suicidal thoughts, or major behavior changes.\n  This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe stomach pain, yellow skin/eyes, or unusual bleeding/bruising with\n  valproate. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Slowed breathing when gabapentin or phenobarbital is combined with opioids,\n  benzodiazepines, alcohol, or other sedating medicines. This is less common but\n  serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label; FDA opioid/CNS depressant safety\n  communication; FDA gabapentin/pregabalin safety communication]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen seizure medicines for interactions, duplicate therapy, levels, renal or\nhepatic dosing, and discharge medication changes. Discuss with the patient only\nif relevant to discharge or home medication use.\n\n\n15. Electrolytes and Supplements\n\nExamples:\nPotassium, magnesium, phosphate, iron, vitamin D, thiamine, folic acid.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This replaces or supports something your body needs.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Iron can cause constipation or dark stool. This is common enough to mention.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Magnesium can cause diarrhea. This is common enough to mention. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- Potassium can irritate the stomach. This is common enough to mention,\n  especially with oral tablets or liquid. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe stomach pain, severe diarrhea, vomiting, chest symptoms, severe\n  weakness, or trouble swallowing tablets. This is less common but important.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen supplements for absorption issues with antibiotics, thyroid medicine, and\nother oral therapies. Discuss timing with the patient only if the medication\nwill continue after discharge.\n\n\n16. Alcohol Withdrawal or Substance-Use Medicines\n\nExamples:\nLorazepam, diazepam, phenobarbital, thiamine, folic acid, multivitamin,\nbuprenorphine, methadone, naltrexone.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication may help treat withdrawal, prevent vitamin problems, reduce\ncravings, or support treatment for opioid use disorder.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, nausea, constipation, or sweating may happen depending\n  on the medication. Sleepiness and dizziness are common enough to mention with\n  sedating withdrawal medicines and opioid-use-disorder medicines. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Very slow breathing, extreme sleepiness, confusion, fainting, or severe\n  dizziness. This is less common but serious. [Source: FDA opioid/benzodiazepine\n  safety communication; DailyMed FDA label]\n- Chest palpitations or fainting with methadone. This is less common but\n  important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMedication history point:\n\"Please tell the team about anything you take at home or outside the hospital.\"\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for opioids, benzodiazepines, phenobarbital, alcohol use, sleep\nmedicines, QT-risk medicines, and other sedating medicines.\n\n\nDocumentation Prompts\n\nDocument per hospital workflow:\n- Medication name\n- Verified indication\n- Main counseling points covered\n- Important warning sign reviewed, if applicable\n- Safety point reviewed, if applicable\n- Interaction concern escalated or pharmacist-reviewed, if applicable\n- Patient/caregiver understanding using teach-back\n- Questions escalated to pharmacist or care team\n\n\nSource Notes\n\nUse hospital-approved references for final verification. Frequency and warning\nsign wording in this guide is intentionally simplified for patient counseling.\nExact percentages should be verified for the exact medication, dose, indication,\nand patient population.\n\n- DailyMed Drug Labels\n  https://dailymed.nlm.nih.gov/dailymed/\n  Use for FDA-approved medication labels, adverse reaction frequency tables,\n  boxed warnings, warnings/precautions, contraindications, and interaction\n  information.\n\n- CDC: Antibiotic Use and Side Effects\n  https://www.cdc.gov/antibiotic-use/\n  Use for patient-friendly antibiotic side-effect counseling.\n\n- CDC: C. diff\n  https://www.cdc.gov/c-diff/\n  Use for antibiotic-associated severe diarrhea and C. diff counseling.\n\n- FDA: Opioid Pain Medicines Safety Information\n  https://www.fda.gov/drugs/information-drug-class/opioid-medications\n  Use for opioid safety, overdose, slowed breathing, dependence, and safe-use\n  counseling.\n\n- FDA: Opioids with Benzodiazepines or Other CNS Depressants\n  https://www.fda.gov/drugs/drug-safety-and-availability/fda-drug-safety-communication-fda-warns-about-serious-risks-and-death-when-combining-opioid\n  Use for serious sedation and breathing-risk counseling when opioids are\n  combined with benzodiazepines, alcohol, sleep medicines, or other CNS\n  depressants.\n\n- FDA: Gabapentin/Pregabalin and Serious Breathing Problems\n  https://www.fda.gov/drugs/drug-safety-and-availability/fda-warns-about-serious-breathing-problems-seizure-and-nerve-pain-medicines-gabapentin\n  Use for breathing-risk counseling when gabapentin or pregabalin is combined\n  with opioids or other CNS depressants, or when patients have respiratory risk\n  factors.\n\n- MedlinePlus: Hypoglycemia\n  https://medlineplus.gov/hypoglycemia.html\n  Use for patient-friendly low blood sugar symptoms.\n\n- MedlinePlus: Prednisone\n  https://medlineplus.gov/druginfo/meds/a601102.html\n  Use for patient-friendly steroid counseling.\n","detailed":"Detailed Medication Guide \n\nThe medication indication, counseling points, as well as every side effect that will be mentioned to the patient must be verified by the pharmacist before the intern counsels. After any student counsels any patient, the pharmacist shall audit the interaction by speaking to the patient after the student does so as a review before signing off on the I-Vent. Confirm the patient-specific indication using the medication order, progress notes, problem list, consult notes, medication history, or pharmacist-confirmed clarification when needed. Do not assume the indication is based only on the medication name or medication class. \n \nThe medication information in this guide should be verified with the hospital\u0027s approved drug information resources, such as Lexicomp, Micromedex, current package inserts, institutional protocols, and pharmacy department policies. This guide is intended to support patient counseling and should not replace clinical judgment or official drug references. \n \nTable of Contents \n \nPart 1: Hospital Focus Medication-Specific Counseling Sections \nA. Antibiotics \n  - Azithromycin \n  - Beta-Lactam Shared Counseling Note \n  - Cefazolin \n  - Cefepime \n  - Ceftriaxone \n  - Daptomycin \n  - Doxycycline \n  - Ertapenem \n  - Aminoglycosides (Gentamicin / Tobramycin) \n  - Quinolones (Levofloxacin / Ciprofloxacin) \n  - Linezolid \n  - Metronidazole \n  - Piperacillin-Tazobactam \n  - Vancomycin IV \n \nB. Anti-coagulants \n  - Unfractionated Heparin IV or Subcutaneous \n  - Enoxaparin \n  - Apixaban \n  - Rivaroxaban \n  - Warfarin \n \nC. Diabetes Medications \n  - Insulin Glargine \n  - Insulin Lispro / Rapid-Acting Insulin \n  - Empagliflozin / Dapagliflozin \n  - Metformin \n \nD. Heart Failure Medications \n  - Sacubitril-Valsartan \n  - Carvedilol \n  - Metoprolol Succinate \n  - Furosemide / Loop Diuretics \n  - Spironolactone \n  - Nitroglycerin \n \nE. Inhalers and Nebulized Respiratory Medications \n  - Albuterol \n  - Ipratropium / Albuterol \n  - Tiotropium \n  - Fluticasone-Salmeterol \n  - Budesonide-Formoterol \n \nF. Transplant Medications \n  - Rejection Prevention / Maintenance Immunosuppression \n    - Tacrolimus \n    - Cyclosporine \n    - Mycophenolate / Mycophenolic Acid \n    - Sirolimus / Everolimus \n    - Belatacept \n  - Rejection Treatment / Desensitization Therapies \n    - Apheresis / IVIG \n    - Antithymocyte Globulin / Thymoglobulin \n  - Infection Prevention / Treatment \n    - Valganciclovir / Ganciclovir \n    - Sulfamethoxazole-Trimethoprim \n    - Atovaquone \n    - Dapsone \n    - Pentamidine \n    - Azole Antifungals \n      - Clotrimazole Troches \n      - Fluconazole \n      - Voriconazole \n      - Posaconazole \n \nPart 2: Additional Common Inpatient Medication Categories \n- Antiplatelets \n- Antivirals and Antifungals \n- Pain Medications: Non-Opioid \n- Pain Medications: Opioids \n- Corticosteroids \n- Blood Pressure Medications \n- Diuretics \n- GI Protection and Acid Suppression \n- Antiemetics and Nausea Medications \n- Bowel Regimen \n- Psychiatric and Sleep Medications \n- Seizure Medications \n- Electrolytes and Supplements \n- Medications for Alcohol Withdrawal or Substance Use \n \n \nA. Antibiotics \nGeneral pharmacist counseling points: \nExplain the suspected or confirmed infection being treated. \nExplain that the antibiotic may change when culture results return or when the patient improves. \nReview allergies, medication adjusted dose per renal/hepatic function, antibiotic duration, and drug-drug interactions. \n \nAzithromycin \nPossible inpatient use: infection, GI motility, etc. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. The antibiotic plan may change as the team reviews culture results and how you are doing. \nCommon side effects: Headache, diarrhea, stomach pain, upset stomach, or throwing up \nImportant interactions to check: QT-prolonging medications, warfarin, digoxin, and other medications with clinically significant arrhythmia or interaction risk. \n \nBeta-Lactam Shared Counseling Note \nIncludes but not limited to: cefazolin, cefepime, ceftriaxone, ertapenem, and piperacillin-tazobactam. \nPharmacist should check: Allergy history, renal dosing, duplicate coverage, and planned duration. \nCommon group side effects: diarrhea, nausea/vomiting, rash, itching, infusion-site issues, and lab abnormalities may occur. C. difficile-associated diarrhea, anaphylaxis, and kidney injury with selected agents are potentially serious but uncommon. \n \nCefazolin \nPossible inpatient use: surgical prophylaxis, skin/soft tissue infection, MSSA infection, selected bloodstream infection, or other gram-positive infection. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. It helps prevent or treat bacteria that are expected to respond to this type of antibiotic. \nCommon side effects: Diarrhea, upset stomach, or throwing up. Decreased appetite. Stomach pain or heartburn. Gas. Headache. Feeling sleepy \n \nCefepime \nPossible inpatient use: broad gram-negative coverage including Pseudomonas risk, febrile neutropenia, pneumonia, urinary infection, sepsis, or hospital-acquired infection. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. It covers a broad range of bacteria, and the team may narrow it once more information is available. \nCommon side effects: Skin rash, N/V/D, passing out, severe fatigue \nShould watch out for any possible or delayed allergic reactions (anaphylaxis, SJS, etc.)  \n \nCeftriaxone \nPossible inpatient use: pneumonia, urinary tract infection, bloodstream infection, intra-abdominal infection with other agents, meningitis, or perioperative/procedural indications. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for indication]. The plan may be adjusted as test results, and your response to treatment becomes clearer. \nCommon side effects: Skin rash, diarrhea, local injection site (if IM). \n \nDaptomycin \nPossible inpatient use: gram-positive infection such as bacteremia, skin/soft tissue infection, VRE infection (excluding pulmonary infections), or other culture-directed therapy. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. Most people tolerate it, but please mention new muscle pain or weakness so the team can check early if needed. \nCommon side effects: Chest pain, edema, dermatologic, diaphoresis, pruritus, skin rash, abdominal pain, diarrhea \nImportant interactions to check: statins or other medications that may increase muscle toxicity risk. \n \nDoxycycline \nPossible inpatient use: atypical respiratory coverage, tick-borne infection, skin/soft tissue infection, MRSA step-down or adjunct therapy, or other culture/protocol-directed use. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. If you take it by mouth, some antacids, vitamins, or minerals can keep it from absorbing well, so timing matters. \nCommon side effects: tetracycline labeling lists nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, rash, photosensitivity, and urticaria. Exact rates vary by formulation and indication. \nImportant interactions to check: oral antacids or supplements containing aluminum, calcium, magnesium, iron, zinc, bismuth, or multivitamins because they may reduce doxycycline absorption; separate administration per hospital policy or drug reference. Also review warfarin. \n \nErtapenem \nPossible inpatient use: intra-abdominal infection, urinary infection, diabetic foot infection, polymicrobial infection, ESBL-producing organism, or once-daily broad gram-negative/anaerobic coverage when Pseudomonas coverage is not needed. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. It covers many types of bacteria, and the team may narrow or stop it when culture results are reviewed. \nCommon side effects: Diarrhea, nausea, headache, anuria, dermatological, abdominal distention \n \nGentamicin / Tobramycin \nPossible inpatient use: severe gram-negative infection, synergy for selected infections, perioperative/protocol-directed use, or inhaled tobramycin in selected pulmonary protocols. Confirm the patient-specific indication and route before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. The team doses it carefully to help it work while lowering the chance of kidney or hearing-related problems. \nCommon side effects: nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity are the most important adverse reactions for systemic aminoglycosides; exact percentages vary widely by dose, duration, renal function, age, dehydration, and concomitant nephrotoxic/ototoxic drugs. \nGentamicin: Decreased appetite, weight loss, headache, upset stomach or throwing up, more saliva, mouth irritation or mouth sores, hair loss, joint pain. \nTobramycin: Headache diarrhea, upset stomach, or throwing up, feeling tired or weak, pain where the shot was given. \nImportant interactions to check include other nephrotoxic or ototoxic medications, loop diuretics, neuromuscular blockers, and other agents that may increase kidney, hearing, or respiratory weakness risk. \n \nLevofloxacin / Ciprofloxacin \nPossible inpatient use: pneumonia, urinary infection, intra-abdominal infection with other agents, gram-negative infection, or oral step-down therapy when appropriate. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. If you take it by mouth, antacids, vitamins, or minerals can reduce absorption, so doses may need to be spaced apart. \nCommon side effects: Upset stomach, diarrhea or constipation, headache. Although it is rare, one should mention risk of tendon injury. \nImportant interactions to check: oral antacids, sucralfate, iron, zinc, magnesium, aluminum, calcium, multivitamins, or other cation-containing products because they may reduce absorption; levofloxacin should be separated by at least 2 hours before or after these products. Also review QT-prolonging medications, warfarin, diabetes medications, steroids, and interacting seizure-risk medications. \n \nLinezolid \nPossible inpatient use: MRSA pneumonia, VRE infection, resistant gram-positive infection, or culture-directed oral/IV therapy. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. The team may review blood counts and certain mood, pain, or nausea medicines because interactions may occur. \nCommon side effects: Diarrhea, decreased white blood cell count, pruritus, skin rash, abdominal pain, N/V, vulvovaginal candidiasis (adults: 1% to 2%) abnormal hepatic function tests, fungal infection, dizziness, headache. Thrombocytopenia is duration-related, generally more likely after more than 2 weeks. \nImportant interactions to check: serotonergic medications such as SSRIs, SNRIs, trazodone, triptans, buspirone, bupropion, and selected opioids such as meperidine or tramadol; MAO inhibitors; adrenergic agents; and high-tyramine foods if relevant to the care plan (Serotonin syndrome risk is uncommon but increases with multiple serotonergic medications; monitoring is often sufficient in the inpatient setting). \n \nMetronidazole \nPossible inpatient use: anaerobic infection, intra-abdominal infection with other agents, C. difficile therapy in selected situations, bacterial vaginosis, or other anaerobic coverage. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. Nausea or a metallic taste can happen, and longer courses may need extra attention to numbness or tingling. \nCommon side effects: Constipation, diarrhea, stomach pain, upset stomach, throwing up, or decreased appetite. Stomach cramps. Metallic taste. Headache. Joint pain. Lowered interest in sex. \n \nImportant interactions to check: warfarin, alcohol or alcohol-containing products when relevant to discharge, disulfiram, lithium, and other medications with neurologic toxicity risk. \n \nPiperacillin-Tazobactam \nPossible inpatient use: broad empiric coverage for sepsis, pneumonia, intra-abdominal infection, urinary infection, diabetic foot infection, or polymicrobial infection. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This antibiotic is being used for [indication]. It is often used while the team gathers more information and may be changed when cultures are reviewed. \nCommon side effects: Diarrhea, pruritus, skin rash, abdominal pain, constipation, dyspepsia, N/V, candidiasis, and headache. \n \nVancomycin IV \nPossible inpatient use: suspected or confirmed MRSA infection, serious gram-positive infection, bacteremia, pneumonia, bone/joint infection, endocarditis, or empiric therapy in high-risk patients. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n Basic counseling point: This IV antibiotic is being used for [indication]. The team may adjust the dose based on kidney function or drug levels. \nCommon side effects: Diarrhea, stomach pain, upset stomach, or throwing up. Infusion reaction/redness/itching, serious skin reactions (rare but important to recognize early). \nApproximate frequency: exact rates vary widely by exposure, kidney function, and concomitant nephrotoxins; labeling lists vancomycin infusion reaction and acute kidney injury among common clinically important reactions. \nImportant interactions to check: nephrotoxic medications, ototoxic medications, IV contrast exposure, and other agents that may increase kidney injury risk. \n \nB. Anticoagulants \n \nGeneral pharmacist counseling points: \nExplain that anticoagulants help prevent or treat blood clots. \nBecause bleeding is the major risk, one should review bleeding side effect, but that benefit outweighs risk, interacting medications, procedures, renal function, platelets, hemoglobin/hematocrit, and the transition plan. \n \nUnfractionated Heparin (IV or Subcutaneous) \nPossible inpatient use: treatment of clots, acute coronary syndrome, bridging therapy, dialysis/line protocols, or clot prevention. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This blood thinner is being used for [indication]. It helps prevent or treat clots, and the team watches closely for bleeding. \nCommon side effects: Signs of bleeding like throwing up or coughing up blood; vomit that looks like coffee grounds; blood in the urine; black, red, or tarry stools; bleeding from the gums; abnormal vaginal bleeding; bruises without a cause or that get bigger; or bleeding you cannot stop. Weakness on 1 side of the body, trouble speaking or thinking, change in balance, drooping on one side of the face, or blurred eyesight, feeling confused, very bad headache. Dizziness or passing out. Upset stomach or throwing up. Injection-site bruising can be mild. \nImportant interactions to check: antiplatelets, NSAIDs, thrombolytics, other anticoagulants, and procedure or neuraxial timing. \n \nEnoxaparin \nPossible inpatient use: VTE prophylaxis, DVT/PE treatment, ACS, bridging, or selected procedure-related use. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This injectable blood thinner is being used for [indication]. The dose depends on whether it is being used to prevent or treat clots. \nCommon side effects: Anemia, hemorrhage, hematuria, thrombocytopenia, bleeding at injection site, hematoma at injection site, pain at injection site  \nSignificance: bruising/injection-site pain is usually mild; bleeding, thrombocytopenia, major anemia, spinal/epidural hematoma risk, and HIT are potentially serious but uncommon. \nImportant interactions to check: antiplatelets, NSAIDs, other anticoagulants, thrombolytics, renal function changes, and procedure or neuraxial timing. \n \nApixaban \nPossible inpatient use: atrial fibrillation stroke prevention, DVT/PE treatment, or continuation of home therapy. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This blood thinner is being used for [indication]. The main thing to know is that it lowers clot risk, but it can also increase bleeding risk. \nCommon side effects: Sins of bleeding like throwing up or coughing up blood; vomit that looks like coffee grounds; blood in the urine; black, red, or tarry stools; bleeding from the gums; abnormal vaginal bleeding; bruises without a cause or that get bigger; or bleeding you cannot stop. Weakness on 1 side of the body, trouble speaking or thinking, change in balance, drooping on one side of the face, or blurred eyesight. Dizziness or passing out. Feeling tired or weak. Feeling confused. Headache. Joint pain or swelling. Chest pain or pressure.Bleeding is the main adverse effect and is clinically significant. Bruising, nosebleed, blood in urine, GI bleeding, and anemia may occur.  \nSignificance: minor bruising may be mild; GI bleeding, intracranial bleeding symptoms, or major hemoglobin drop should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: strong CYP3A4/P-gp inhibitors or inducers, antiplatelets, NSAIDs, other anticoagulants, and procedure timing. \n \nRivaroxaban \nPossible inpatient use: atrial fibrillation stroke prevention, DVT/PE treatment, VTE prophylaxis in selected settings, or continuation of home therapy. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This blood thinner is being used for [indication]. It lowers clot risk, and some doses work best when taken with food. \nCommon side effects: bleeding is the main adverse effect and is clinically significant. Signs of bleeding like throwing up or coughing up blood; vomit that looks like coffee grounds; blood in the urine; black, red, or tarry stools; bleeding from the gums; abnormal vaginal bleeding; bruises without a cause or that get bigger; or bleeding you cannot stop. Signs of a ruptured spleen like left upper stomach pain, pain below the left rib cage, pain at the tip of the left shoulder, or general stomach pain. Weakness on 1 side of the body, trouble speaking or thinking, change in balance, drooping on one side of the face, or blurred eyesight. Dizziness or passing out. Severe headache or throwing up. Pain, swelling, or new drainage at wound sites. \nSignificance: minor bruising may be mild; major bleeding, major anemia, intracranial bleeding symptoms, or GI bleeding should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: strong CYP3A4/P-gp inhibitors or inducers, antiplatelets, NSAIDs, other anticoagulants, procedure timing, and food requirement for higher-dose regimens. \n \n \nWarfarin \nPossible inpatient use: mechanical valve, atrial fibrillation, VTE treatment, antiphospholipid syndrome, or continuation of home therapy. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This blood thinner is being used for [verified reason]. Blood tests called INR help guide the dose, and diet or medication changes can affect it. \nCommon side effects: Bleeding problems like bruising; black, tarry, or bloody stools; bleeding gums; blood in the urine; coughing up blood; cuts that take a long time to stop bleeding; feel dizzy; feeling very tired or weak; nosebleeds; pain or swelling; throwing up blood or throw up that looks like coffee grounds; or very bad headache. Vaginal bleeding that is not normal or very heavy periods (menstrual bleeding). Weakness on 1 side of the body, trouble speaking or thinking, change in balance, drooping on one side of the face, or blurred eyesight. Chest pain. Severe dizziness or passing out. Swelling, warmth, numbness, change of color, or pain in a leg or arm. Very bad headache. Feeling very tired or weak. Swelling. Change in skin color to black or purple. Pain, color, or temperature change in any part of the body. Kidney problems like not able to pass urine, change in how much urine is passed, blood in the urine, or a big weight gain. \nSignificance: any suspected major bleeding should be evaluated promptly if suspected. Skin necrosis and purple toe syndrome are rare but important to recognize early. \nImportant interactions to check: antibiotics, antifungals, amiodarone, antiepileptic drugs, antiplatelets, NSAIDs, other anticoagulants, herbal products, alcohol use, and major diet changes involving vitamin K. \n \nC. Diabetes Medications \n \nGeneral pharmacist counseling points: \nExplain that illness, steroids, nutrition changes, tube feeds, procedures, and kidney function can change blood sugar needs in the hospital. \nTeach hypoglycemia symptoms and explain that low blood sugar symptoms require prompt attention in the hospital. \nReview renal function, steroid use, nutrition status, insulin transitions, duplicate therapy, and held home medications. \n \nInsulin Glargine \nPossible inpatient use: basal insulin for background glucose control. Confirm the patient-specific indication and glucose plan before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This insulin is being used as part of your blood sugar plan. It usually provides longer background blood sugar control when that matches your ordered regimen. \nCommon side effects: hypoglycemia is common and can become serious if not treated; injection-site reaction, allergic reaction, edema, weight gain, rash, and low potassium are recognized adverse effects. Labeling does not provide one useful hypoglycemia percentage because rates vary by regimen and glucose targets. \nSignificance: mild hypoglycemia symptoms are clinically significant; very low blood sugar with confusion, seizure, or inability to swallow should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: medications that increase hypoglycemia risk and beta-blockers, which may mask some hypoglycemia symptoms. \n \nInsulin Lispro / Rapid-Acting Insulin \nPossible inpatient use: mealtime insulin, correction insulin, or other inpatient glucose management protocol. Confirm the patient-specific glucose plan before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This insulin is being used as part of your blood sugar plan. It usually works around meals or to correct high blood sugar, depending on your orders. \nCommon side effects: hypokalemia, hypoglycemia is the most common adverse reaction of insulin therapy and may be life-threatening. Injection-site reactions can occur; infusion-site reactions in one pediatric pump study were reported around 21% with insulin lispro versus 17% with insulin aspart. \nSignificance: mild symptoms are clinically significant; very low blood sugar should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: medication or nutrition changes that increase hypoglycemia risk, beta-blockers that may mask symptoms, and steroid changes that may increase insulin requirements. \n \nEmpagliflozin / Dapagliflozin \nPossible inpatient use: heart failure benefit, CKD/diabetes continuation in selected stable patients, or home medication review. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling; these medications are often held during acute illness, surgery, poor intake, DKA risk, or instability. \nBasic counseling point: This medication is being used for [indication]. It is sometimes paused in the hospital during illness, procedures, poor intake, or dehydration risk. \nCommon side effects: urinary tract infections and female genital mycotic infections. Volume depletion is clinically significant, especially with concomitant use with diuretics. \nSignificance: genital yeast infection or mild UTI may be mild to clinically significant; euglycemic ketoacidosis, serious UTI/urosepsis, Fournier gangrene, or marked dehydration should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: diuretics, low oral intake, perioperative status, acute illness, insulin dose changes, and other factors that increase dehydration or ketoacidosis risk. \n \nMetformin \nPossible inpatient use: diabetes management continuation in selected stable patients or medication history review. Confirm the patient-specific indication and whether it is being continued or held before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This medication is being used for [verified reason], or it may be reviewed as a home medication. It is sometimes held during kidney changes, contrast studies, or acute illness. \nCommon side effects: diarrhea, nausea, abdominal discomfort, and metallic taste are common; exact rates vary by formulation and dose. Lactic acidosis is rare but important to recognize early. \nSignificance: GI upset is usually mild; lactic acidosis risk should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: iodinated contrast exposure, acute kidney injury, severe illness, hypoxia, alcohol use, and other factors that increase lactic acidosis risk. \n \n \n \n \nD. Heart Failure Medications \n \nGeneral pharmacist counseling points: \n- Explain that these medications help remove extra fluid, protect the heart, lower readmission risk, and improve survival depending on the class. \n- Review blood pressure, heart rate, kidney function, potassium, magnesium, weight, volume status, dizziness/falls, and medication sequencing. \n \nSacubitril-Valsartan \nPossible inpatient use: guideline-directed therapy for heart failure when blood pressure, renal function, and potassium allow. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This medication is being used for [verified reason]. It can help protect the heart over time, and the team checks blood pressure, kidney function, and potassium. \nCommon side effects: hypotension, hyperkalemia, cough, dizziness, renal failure/acute renal failure. \nImportant interactions to check: ACE inhibitors within 36 hours, duplicate ARB therapy, aliskiren when contraindicated, potassium supplements, potassium-sparing diuretics, TMP-SMX, and other hyperkalemia-risk increasing medications. \n \nCarvedilol \nPossible inpatient use: heart failure beta-blocker, hypertension, rate control, or post-MI care. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This medication is being used for [verified reason]. It can slow the heart rate or lower blood pressure, so dizziness or tiredness can happen during dose changes. \nCommon side effects: dizziness 24% to 32% in heart failure trials (clinically significant for falls), fatigue about 24% in mild-to-moderate HF, bradycardia 9% to 14% (clinically significant), hypotension 3% to 8% in trial tables and postural hypotension/hypotension 9.7% in some HF trials (clinically significant), diarrhea about 5% to 12% (usually mild/manage), hyperglycemia about 5% to 12% (clinically significant in diabetes). \nImportant interactions to check: other heart-rate-lowering medications, insulin or diabetes medications because hypoglycemia symptoms may be masked, and CYP2D6 inhibitors when clinically relevant. \n \nMetoprolol Succinate \nPossible inpatient use: heart failure beta-blocker, rate control, hypertension, or post-MI care. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This medication is being used for [indication]. It can help with heart rate, blood pressure, or heart protection depending on the plan. \nCommon side effects: Bradycardia (including sinus pause: 2% to 16%) (table 1), hypotension (1% to 27%), tiredness, dizziness. \nSignificance: fatigue may be mild/manage; bradycardia, hypotension, syncope, bronchospasm, or worsening HF symptoms are clinically significant and may need prompt evaluation. \nImportant interactions to check: other heart-rate-lowering medications, insulin or diabetes medications because hypoglycemia symptoms may be masked, and CYP2D6 inhibitors when clinically relevant. \n \nFurosemide / Loop Diuretics \nPossible inpatient use: fluid overload in heart failure, kidney disease, liver disease, pulmonary edema, or edema management. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This medication is being used for [indication]. It helps the body remove extra fluid, so more urination is expected. \nCommon side effects: frequent urination is expected; low potassium/magnesium, dehydration, dizziness, kidney function changes, low blood pressure, and hearing changes can occur. Exact percentages vary by dose and population. \nSignificance: increased urination is expected/mild; symptomatic hypotension, major electrolyte abnormality, acute kidney injury, or hearing changes are clinically significant and may need prompt evaluation. \nImportant interactions to check: nephrotoxic medications, aminoglycosides, lithium, digoxin risk with electrolyte abnormalities, and other medications that lower blood pressure or electrolytes. \n \n \nSpironolactone \nPossible inpatient use: heart failure mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist, resistant hypertension, cirrhosis-related ascites, or hypokalemia-sparing diuresis. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This medication is being used for [indication]. It can affect potassium levels, so the team reviews potassium and kidney function. \nCommon side effects: gynecomastia is the most common adverse reaction; in RALES, about 9% of male subjects developed gynecomastia, up to 52% in patients receiving high doses [eg, ≥150 mg/day]) Hyperkalemia is clinically significant and can become serious and should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nSignificance: breast tenderness/gynecomastia is usually mild to clinically significant; hyperkalemia, major kidney dysfunction, or arrhythmia symptoms should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: potassium supplements, ACE inhibitors, ARBs, ARNIs, TMP-SMX, tacrolimus, cyclosporine, and other hyperkalemia-risk medications. \n \nNitroglycerin \nPossible inpatient use: chest pain/angina, hypertensive emergency with ischemia, acute pulmonary edema, or peri-procedure blood pressure control. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This medication is being used for [verified reason]. It relaxes blood vessels; headache or dizziness can happen, and certain erectile dysfunction medicines must be avoided with it. \nCommon side effects: Headache (patch, rectal ointment: 63% to 64%; lingual spray, sublingual powder: \u003e2%), hypotension (patch: ≤4%; including orthostatic hypotension), syncope (patch: ≤4%), Dizziness (lingual spray, patch, rectal ointment, sublingual powder: 2% to 6%). Flushing and low blood pressure are common; exact percentages vary by formulation and indication. \nSignificance: headache may be mild, very low blood pressure, syncope, persistent chest pain, or PDE-5 inhibitor interaction should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: PDE-5 inhibitors such as sildenafil, tadalafil, or vardenafil; riociguat; and other medications that may cause very low blood pressure. \n \n \nE. Inhalers and Nebulized Respiratory Medications \n \nGeneral pharmacist counseling points: \n- Explain rescue versus maintenance therapy. \n- Review whether breathing symptoms are improving and whether the medication is rescue or maintenance therapy. \n- If the medication continues after discharge, pharmacy or respiratory therapy should review inhaler technique, spacer use, and mouth rinsing for inhaled steroids. \n \nAlbuterol \nPossible inpatient use: rescue bronchodilator for wheezing, asthma/COPD exacerbation, bronchospasm, or hyperkalemia adjunct in selected cases. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This breathing medication is being used for [verified reason]. It helps open the airways, and shakiness or a faster heartbeat can happen. \nCommon side effects: Nervousness (4% to 15%), tremor (5% to 38%), Bronchospasm (8% to 15%; exacerbation of underlying pulmonary disease), exacerbation of asthma (11% to 13%), pharyngitis (14%), rhinitis (5% to 16%), upper respiratory tract infection (5% to 21%), tachycardia (1% to 7%), unpleasant taste (inhalation site: 4%), vomiting (3% to 7%), Hypersensitivity reaction (3% to 6%), respiratory system disorder (6%), sinusitis (≥5%), throat irritation (10%), upper respiratory tract inflammation (5%), viral upper respiratory tract infection (7%), wheezing (1% to 2%, fever (5% to 6%) \nSignificance: tremor/nervousness can be mild; tachycardia, chest pain, paradoxical bronchospasm, or significant hypokalemia can become serious and should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: beta-blockers, other sympathomimetics, medications that lower potassium, and QT- or heart-rate-risk medications when clinically relevant. \n \nIpratropium / Albuterol \nPossible inpatient use: COPD exacerbation, asthma exacerbation adjunct, or bronchospasm treatment. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This breathing treatment is being used for [indication]. It helps open the airways, and dry mouth, shakiness, or a faster heartbeat can happen. \nCommon side effects: Chest Pain (3%), headache (3%), albuterol-related tremor/nervousness/palpitations plus ipratropium-related dry mouth and throat irritation; exact percentages vary by product and setting. \nSignificance: dry mouth is usually mild; urinary retention, eye pain/blurred vision from nebulizer exposure, paradoxical bronchospasm, or concerning palpitations are clinically significant and may need prompt evaluation. \nImportant interactions to check: duplicate bronchodilators, beta-blockers, other anticholinergic medications, and medications that may worsen urinary retention or glaucoma risk. \n \nTiotropium \nPossible inpatient use: maintenance bronchodilator for COPD or add-on maintenance therapy for asthma. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \nBasic counseling point: This inhaled medication is being used for [indication]. It is usually a maintenance breathing medicine, not a quick rescue treatment. \nCommon side effects: Xerostomia (4% to 16%), [haryngitis (9% to 16%), sinusitis (3% to 11%), upper respiratory tract infection (41%), Angina pectoris (1% to 3%; includes exacerbation of angina pectoris), chest pain (≤7%), edema (dependent: 5%), palpitations (≤3%), Pruritus (1% to 3%), skin rash (1% to 4%), Abdominal pain (5%; upper abdominal pain: \u003c1%), constipation (1% to 5%), diarrhea (1% to 2%), dyspepsia (6%), gastroesophageal reflux disease (≤3%), oropharyngeal candidiasis (1% to 3%), stomatitis (includes ulcerative stomatitis: 1% to 3%), vomiting (4%), Urinary tract infection (1% to 7%), Candidiasis (4%), infection (4%), headache (4% to 6%) \nSpiriva HandiHaler labeling reports pharyngitis 12.5%, sinusitis 6.5%, headache 5.7%, constipation 5.1%, dry mouth 5.1%, depression 4.4%, insomnia 4.4%, and arthralgia 4.2%. Respimat COPD trials report pharyngitis, cough, dry mouth, and sinusitis above 3%. \nSignificance: dry mouth/constipation are usually mild; urinary retention, eye pain or vision changes, or paradoxical bronchospasm should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \nImportant interactions to check: duplicate LAMA/SAMA therapy and other anticholinergic medications. \n \nFluticasone-Salmeterol \n- Possible inpatient use: maintenance therapy for asthma or COPD when inhaled steroid/LABA is indicated. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This inhaler is being used for [verified reason]. It is usually a maintenance inhaler, and rinsing the mouth after use helps lower the chance of thrush if continued. \n- Common side effects: asthma labeling lists upper respiratory tract infection/inflammation, pharyngitis, dysphonia, oral candidiasis, bronchitis, cough, headache, nausea, and vomiting. COPD labeling lists pneumonia, oral candidiasis, throat irritation, dysphonia, viral respiratory infections, headache, and musculoskeletal pain. COPD pneumonia rates in some labeling are reported as 84 to 88 events per 1,000 treatment-years with fluticasone-containing groups versus 52 events per 1,000 treatment-years in comparator groups. \n- Significance: hoarseness/thrush are usually mild to clinically significant; pneumonia, paradoxical bronchospasm, or serious LABA-related cardiac symptoms should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: duplicate LABA/ICS therapy, strong CYP3A4 inhibitors, beta-blockers, and QT- or heart-rate-risk medications when clinically relevant. \n \nBudesonide-Formoterol \n- Possible inpatient use: maintenance asthma/COPD therapy or another protocol-based respiratory plan. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling; inpatient use should follow hospital protocol. \n- Basic counseling point: This inhaler is being used for [verified reason]. How it is used depends on the hospital plan and whether it is meant for maintenance, reliever use, or both. \n- Common side effects: COPD labeling includes nasopharyngitis, oral candidiasis, bronchitis, sinusitis, and upper respiratory tract infections; one asthma table reports oral candidiasis around 1.4% with budesonide-formoterol 80/4.5. Lung infections other than pneumonia, mostly bronchitis, occurred 7.9% with Symbicort 160/4.5 versus placebo in one COPD trial summary. \n- Significance: thrush/hoarseness are mild to clinically significant; pneumonia, paradoxical bronchospasm, or concerning palpitations should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: duplicate LABA/ICS therapy, strong CYP3A4 inhibitors, beta-blockers, and QT- or heart-rate-risk medications when clinically relevant. \n \nF. Transplant Medications \n \nGeneral pharmacist counseling points: \n- Explain that transplant medications prevent rejection, treat rejection, or prevent infections while the immune system is suppressed. \n- Review transplant organ, transplant date, home regimen, missed doses before admission, drug levels, kidney/liver function, blood counts, electrolytes, infection symptoms, and all interacting medications. \n \nRejection Prevention / Maintenance Immunosuppression \n \nTacrolimus \n- Possible inpatient use: maintenance immunosuppression or rejection treatment/prevention. Confirm the patient-specific transplant plan before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This transplant medication is being used for [verified reason]. It helps lower immune activity, and drug levels are important so the amount stays in the right range. \n- Common side effects: tremor, headache, diarrhea, hypertension, nausea, abnormal renal function, insomnia, high potassium, low magnesium, high blood sugar, infection, anemia, and edema are common to very common. Labeling reports many adverse reactions at 30% or more in kidney transplant patients and 40% or more in liver transplant patients depending on regimen. \n- Significance: mild tremor/headache may be clinically significant if level-related; kidney injury, neurotoxicity, very high potassium, infection, and high levels should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: azole antifungals, macrolides, diltiazem/verapamil, amiodarone, protease inhibitors, rifampin, phenytoin, carbamazepine, phenobarbital, grapefruit products, nephrotoxic medications, and hyperkalemia-risk medications. \n \nCyclosporine \n- Possible inpatient use: maintenance immunosuppression or rejection prevention/treatment. Confirm the patient-specific transplant plan before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This transplant medication is being used for [verified reason]. It lowers immune activity, and the team reviews levels, kidney function, blood pressure, and interactions. \n- Common side effects: kidney dysfunction, tremor, hypertension, high potassium, gum overgrowth, increased hair growth, and infection risk. Hypertension occurs in approximately 50% of renal transplant patients and in most cardiac transplant patients in labeling. \n- Significance: cosmetic effects may be mild to clinically significant; kidney injury, very high blood pressure, neurotoxicity, infection, and high levels should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: azole antifungals, macrolides, diltiazem/verapamil, amiodarone, rifampin, seizure medications, statins, grapefruit products, nephrotoxic medications, and hyperkalemia-risk medications. \n \nMycophenolate / Mycophenolic Acid \n- Possible inpatient use: maintenance immunosuppression. Confirm the patient-specific transplant or immunosuppression indication before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This transplant medication is being used for [verified reason]. It lowers immune activity, so diarrhea, infection symptoms, or blood count changes are important to recognize early. \n- Common side effects: diarrhea, leukopenia, infection, vomiting, anemia, thrombocytopenia, and opportunistic infections. Labeling reports diarrhea, leukopenia, infection, and vomiting as common, with several occurring in 20% or more depending on organ type/regimen. \n- Significance: mild GI upset may be mild/manage; persistent, bloody, or severe diarrhea, leukopenia, infection, or GI bleeding should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: antacids, magnesium/aluminum products, bile acid sequestrants, PPIs per institutional guidance, antivirals, and other marrow-suppressive medications. \n \nSirolimus / Everolimus \n- Possible inpatient use: maintenance immunosuppression or conversion regimen. Confirm the patient-specific transplant or immunosuppression plan before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This transplant medication is being used for [verified reason]. It lowers immune activity, and the team may pay extra attention to mouth sores, swelling, wound healing, and interactions. \n- Common side effects: sirolimus renal-transplant labeling reports several adverse reactions at 30% or more, including edema, high triglycerides, hypertension, high cholesterol, increased creatinine, abdominal pain, diarrhea, headache, fever, UTI, anemia, nausea, pain, and thrombocytopenia. Everolimus transplant data include peripheral edema around 45%, hyperlipidemia around 21%, and stomatitis/mouth ulceration around 8% in one kidney transplant study. \n- Significance: mouth sores/edema may be clinically significant; poor wound healing, cytopenias, pneumonitis symptoms, proteinuria, serious infection, or high levels should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: azole antifungals, macrolides, diltiazem/verapamil, rifampin, seizure medications, grapefruit products, statins, and other CYP3A/P-gp modifiers. \n \nBelatacept \n- Possible inpatient use: kidney transplant maintenance immunosuppression or transplant-team-directed conversion from another regimen. Confirm EBV status, transplant indication, and transplant-team plan before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This IV transplant medication is being used for [verified reason]. The transplant team confirms the infusion schedule and makes sure it fits your transplant plan. \n- Common side effects: anemia, diarrhea, urinary tract infection, peripheral edema, constipation, hypertension, fever, graft dysfunction, cough, nausea, vomiting, headache, potassium changes, and leukopenia are common in labeling. \n- Significance: mild GI symptoms or headache may be mild/manage; serious infection, post-transplant lymphoproliferative disorder risk, malignancy risk, graft dysfunction, infusion reaction, or cytopenias are potentially serious but uncommon. \n- Important interactions to check: other immunosuppressants, live vaccines, infection risk with additive immunosuppression, and timing with antithymocyte globulin because allograft thrombosis has been reported when given at the same or nearly the same time in some patients. \n \nRejection Treatment / Desensitization Therapies \n \nApheresis / IVIG \n- Possible inpatient use: antibody-mediated rejection treatment, desensitization protocol, or other transplant-team-directed therapy. Confirm whether apheresis, IVIG, or both are being used and clarify the protocol-specific purpose before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This treatment is being used for [verified reason]. It may help with antibody-related transplant plans, and the transplant team guides the timing and details. \n- Common side effects: apheresis may cause low blood pressure, dizziness, tingling from citrate/calcium shifts, bleeding or line-related issues, and fatigue. IVIG may cause headache, chills, fever, nausea, infusion reactions, fluid overload, kidney dysfunction, thrombosis, hemolysis, or aseptic meningitis. \n- Significance: mild headache, chills, or fatigue may be mild/manage; thrombosis, serious infusion reaction, kidney injury, hemolysis, line complications, or significant blood pressure/electrolyte changes are potentially serious but uncommon. \n- Important interactions to check: nephrotoxic medications, diuretics or fluid-sensitive conditions, thrombosis-risk factors, anticoagulants/antiplatelets around line placement or apheresis, and live vaccines after IVIG because passive antibodies may reduce vaccine response. \n \nAntithymocyte Globulin / Thymoglobulin \n- Possible inpatient use: induction immunosuppression or rejection treatment, especially in transplant-team-directed protocols. Confirm product, indication, dose plan, premedication plan, and protocol before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This IV transplant medication is being used for [verified reason]. The team gives it with close observation because infusion reactions and blood count changes can happen. \n- Common side effects: fever, chills, infusion reactions, headache, nausea, shortness of breath, blood pressure changes, high potassium, low white blood cells, low platelets, infection risk, rash, and serum sickness-like reactions may occur. \n- Significance: chills or mild infusion symptoms may be clinically significant; anaphylaxis, serious infusion reaction, very low blood counts, serious infection, serum sickness, or cardiopulmonary symptoms are potentially serious but uncommon. \n- Important interactions to check: other immunosuppressants, live vaccines, anticoagulants or antiplatelets when thrombocytopenia/procedure risk is relevant, and additive cytopenia or infection-risk medications. \n \nInfection Prevention / Treatment \n \nValganciclovir / Ganciclovir \n- Possible inpatient use: CMV prophylaxis or treatment. Confirm the patient-specific indication, prophylaxis plan, or treatment plan before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This antiviral is being used for [verified reason]. It helps prevent or treat CMV, and kidney function and blood counts help guide safe dosing. \n- Common side effects: diarrhea about 30%, nausea about 23%, vomiting about 16%, headache about 22%, insomnia about 16% in one solid-organ transplant study; neutropenia, anemia, leukopenia, thrombocytopenia, fever, fatigue, UTI, and vomiting are reported at 20% or more across indications. \n- Significance: GI upset may be mild to clinically significant; neutropenia, anemia, thrombocytopenia, and infection risk should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: mycophenolate, TMP-SMX, linezolid, chemotherapy, zidovudine, and other marrow-suppressive or nephrotoxic medications. \n \nSulfamethoxazole-Trimethoprim \n- Possible inpatient use: Pneumocystis pneumonia prophylaxis or treatment, urinary infection, or selected bacterial infections. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This medication is being used for [verified reason]. It may prevent or treat certain infections, and the team checks kidney function, potassium, rash, and blood counts. \n- Common side effects: nausea, rash, diarrhea, creatinine rise, high potassium, and cytopenias; exact percentages vary by dose and indication. \n- Significance: mild nausea may be mild/manage; new, widespread, blistering, or severe rash, anaphylaxis, cytopenias, kidney injury, or hyperkalemia should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: warfarin, ACE inhibitors, ARBs, ARNIs, spironolactone, tacrolimus, cyclosporine, potassium supplements, methotrexate, phenytoin, and other hyperkalemia or marrow-suppression risks. \n \nAtovaquone \n- Possible inpatient use: Pneumocystis pneumonia prophylaxis or treatment alternative when sulfamethoxazole-trimethoprim is not appropriate, or other protocol-directed transplant infection prevention. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This medication is being used for [verified reason]. It helps prevent or treat certain infections when the immune system is lowered, and taking it with food may help it work better if the patient is eating. \n- Common side effects: nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, headache, rash, and liver enzyme abnormalities may occur; exact rates vary by indication and formulation. \n- Significance: mild GI symptoms may be mild/manage; severe rash, persistent vomiting/diarrhea, poor oral intake affecting absorption, or liver injury should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: rifampin, rifabutin, tetracycline, metoclopramide, warfarin, and food or enteral nutrition issues that may affect absorption. \n \nDapsone \n- Possible inpatient use: Pneumocystis pneumonia prophylaxis alternative when sulfamethoxazole-trimethoprim is not appropriate, or other protocol-directed transplant infection prevention. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This medication is being used for [verified reason]. It helps prevent certain infections, and the team checks blood counts and oxygen-related symptoms to keep therapy safe. \n- Common side effects: nausea, rash, anemia/hemolysis, methemoglobinemia symptoms, and liver enzyme abnormalities may occur; exact rates vary by dose, duration, G6PD status, and patient population. \n- Significance: mild nausea may be mild/manage; shortness of breath, blue or gray lips, severe fatigue, dark urine, severe rash, hemolysis, methemoglobinemia, cytopenias, or liver injury should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: G6PD status per institutional policy, other marrow-suppressive medications, trimethoprim, rifampin, and medications or conditions that may increase hemolysis or methemoglobinemia risk. \n \nPentamidine \n- Possible inpatient use: Pneumocystis pneumonia prophylaxis or treatment alternative when other options are not appropriate; may be inhaled or IV depending on indication and protocol. Confirm the route, indication, and transplant protocol before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This medication is being used for [verified reason]. It helps prevent or treat a specific pneumonia risk in patients with lowered immune systems, and side effects depend on whether it is inhaled or given IV. \n- Common side effects: inhaled pentamidine may cause cough, bronchospasm, throat irritation, or unpleasant taste. IV pentamidine may cause nausea, low blood pressure, kidney dysfunction, electrolyte changes, low or high blood sugar, pancreatitis, and blood count changes. \n- Significance: mild cough or throat irritation may be mild/manage; breathing difficulty, significant blood pressure changes, kidney injury, blood sugar problems, pancreatitis symptoms, arrhythmia risk, or severe electrolyte abnormalities should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: nephrotoxic medications, QT-prolonging medications, medications affecting potassium or magnesium, diabetes medications or insulin, and other agents that may increase kidney, electrolyte, or arrhythmia risk. \n \nAzole Antifungals \n \nClotrimazole Troches \n- Possible inpatient use: oral troches for prevention or treatment of oral candidiasis, also called thrush, in transplant or immunocompromised patients. Confirm the patient-specific indication and protocol before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This medication is used in the mouth for [verified reason], often to help prevent or treat thrush. It works best when the troche dissolves slowly in the mouth rather than being chewed or swallowed whole. \n- Common side effects: mouth irritation, nausea, unpleasant taste, and mild GI upset may occur; exact rates vary by use and patient population. \n- Significance: mild taste change or mouth irritation may be mild/manage; worsening mouth pain, trouble swallowing, rash, or signs of allergic reaction should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: tacrolimus or other transplant medication levels when clinically relevant, and timing or administration issues that may affect local effect in the mouth. \n \nFluconazole \n- Possible inpatient use: prevention or treatment of fungal infection in transplant or immunocompromised patients. Confirm the patient-specific indication, duration, and transplant protocol before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This antifungal is being used for [verified reason]. It can interact with transplant medications, so the team may adjust doses or follow levels. \n- Common side effects: nausea, abdominal discomfort, diarrhea, headache, rash, liver enzyme elevation, and QT-related risk may occur; exact rates vary by indication and duration. \n- Significance: mild GI symptoms or headache may be mild/manage; liver injury, serious rash, QT-related symptoms, or major immunosuppressant level increases are potentially serious but uncommon. \n- Important interactions to check: tacrolimus, cyclosporine, sirolimus, everolimus, warfarin, certain statins, QT-prolonging medications, phenytoin, sulfonylureas, and other CYP-metabolized medications. \n \nVoriconazole \n- Possible inpatient use: invasive Aspergillus treatment or serious fungal infection prophylaxis/treatment. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This antifungal is being used for [verified reason]. Temporary vision changes can happen, and interactions with transplant medications are important. \n- Common side effects: visual disturbances 18.7%, fever 5.7%, nausea 5.4%, rash 5.3%, vomiting 4.4%, chills 3.7%, headache 3.0%, increased liver function tests 2.7%, tachycardia 2.4%, hallucinations 2.4%. \n- Significance: transient visual symptoms may be mild/manage; hallucinations, liver injury, serious rash, QT issues, or major immunosuppressant level increases should be evaluated promptly if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: tacrolimus, cyclosporine, sirolimus, everolimus, warfarin, statins, seizure medications, QT-prolonging medications, rifamycins, and other CYP-metabolized medications. \n \nPosaconazole \n- Possible inpatient use: invasive fungal infection prophylaxis or treatment in high-risk immunocompromised/transplant patients. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- Basic counseling point: This antifungal is being used for [verified reason]. The form of the medication and how it is absorbed can matter, and it can interact with transplant medications. \n- Common side effects: delayed-release tablet prophylaxis labeling reports diarrhea 29%, fever 28%, nausea 27%, low potassium 22%, peripheral edema 16%, thrombocytopenia 14%, mucosal inflammation 14%, headache 14%, vomiting 13%, abdominal pain 11%, anemia 10%, constipation 10%, chills 10%, weakness/asthenia 10%, and low magnesium 10%. \n- Significance: GI effects may be mild to clinically significant; electrolyte abnormalities, QT risk, liver injury, thrombocytopenia, and immunosuppressant interactions may need prompt evaluation if suspected. \n- Important interactions to check: tacrolimus, cyclosporine, sirolimus, everolimus, statins, warfarin, QT-prolonging medications, rifamycins, and other CYP3A substrates. Formulation and food requirements may affect absorption. \n \nPart 2: Additional Common Inpatient Medication Categories \n \nUse Part 2 as a supplemental reference for medication categories that are common in the hospital but are not the pharmacy department\u0027s primary counseling focus. The seizure medication section is intentionally more detailed because of hospital unit needs. \n \nImportant navigation note: \n- If a medication or category appears in both Part 1 and Part 2, use the more detailed Part 1 entry for patient counseling. \n- Part 2 broad-category summaries are intended for quick orientation only. \n- For the hospital\u0027s priority counseling groups, Part 1 is the primary working section. \n \n1. Antiplatelets \n \nExamples: \n- Aspirin \n- Clopidogrel \n- Ticagrelor \n- Prasugrel \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- These medications help prevent platelets from forming clots. \n- They are commonly used after stroke, heart attack, or cardiac stent placement. \n- Ticagrelor may cause shortness of breath in some patients. \n- Notify the pharmacist or provider about any home NSAID use or other medications that may increase bleeding risk. \n- Important interactions to check: anticoagulants, NSAIDs, SSRIs/SNRIs when bleeding risk is relevant, thrombolytics, and procedure timing. \n \n2. Antivirals and Antifungals \n \nExamples: \n- Acyclovir \n- Valacyclovir \n- Oseltamivir \n- Fluconazole \n- Micafungin \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- These medications treat viral or fungal infections. \n- Some antifungals interact with anticoagulants, statins, seizure medications, and QT-prolonging medications. \n- The pharmacist may review home medications before discharge if therapy continues. \n- Important interactions to check: azole antifungals with transplant medications, anticoagulants, statins, QT-prolonging medications, and seizure medications; nephrotoxic medications with acyclovir or related antivirals. \n \n3. Pain Medications: Non-Opioid \n \nExamples: \n- Acetaminophen \n- Ibuprofen \n- Ketorolac \n- Naproxen \n- Lidocaine patches \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- Acetaminophen can help with pain or fever but can harm the liver if too much is taken. \n- The team tracks total acetaminophen exposure, including combination products. \n- NSAIDs such as ibuprofen, naproxen, and ketorolac may increase bleeding risk, kidney injury, blood pressure, and stomach irritation. \n- NSAIDs may be avoided or limited in the hospital because of kidney disease, bleeding risk, anticoagulant therapy, heart failure, stomach ulcers, or other risk factors. \n- Review whether pain control is adequate and whether side effects are limiting therapy. \n- Important interactions to check: duplicate acetaminophen products; NSAIDs with anticoagulants, antiplatelets, steroids, ACE inhibitors, ARBs, diuretics, lithium, methotrexate, or kidney-risk medications. \n \n4. Pain Medications: Opioids \n \nExamples: \n- Oxycodone \n- Hydromorphone \n- Morphine \n- Fentanyl \n- Hydrocodone-acetaminophen \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- Opioids are used for moderate to severe pain. In the hospital, the nurse administers them according to the care team\u0027s orders and safety checks. \n- Common side effects include drowsiness, constipation, nausea, dizziness, and falls. \n- Serious risks include slowed breathing, overdose, dependence, and accidental ingestion by children or others. \n- The pharmacist should review opioid safety, bowel regimen, safe storage, disposal, and naloxone if opioids are prescribed at discharge. \n- Important interactions to check: benzodiazepines, gabapentinoids, sleep medications, alcohol, other CNS depressants, serotonergic medications for selected opioids, and duplicate acetaminophen-containing opioid products. \n \n5. Corticosteroids \n \nExamples: \n- Prednisone \n- Methylprednisolone \n- Dexamethasone \n- Hydrocortisone \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- Steroids reduce inflammation and may be used for asthma, COPD, allergic reactions, autoimmune conditions, adrenal issues, or other conditions. \n- Common side effects include increased appetite, mood changes, insomnia, fluid retention, and increased blood sugar. \n- Steroids may increase infection risk. \n- If prescribed a steroid taper at discharge, review the taper calendar carefully. \n- Important interactions to check: diabetes medications, NSAIDs or anticoagulants when GI bleeding risk is relevant, CYP3A inhibitors or inducers for selected steroids, and live vaccines when applicable. \n \n6. Blood Pressure Medications \n \nExamples: \n- Lisinopril \n- Losartan \n- Amlodipine \n- Metoprolol \n- Carvedilol \n- Hydralazine \n- Nifedipine \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- These medications may be used for blood pressure, heart failure, kidney protection, heart rhythm, or post-heart attack care. \n- Counsel on dizziness, lightheadedness, and fall precautions while hospitalized. \n- Encourage slow position changes from lying to sitting or standing. \n- ACE inhibitors such as lisinopril may cause cough or, rarely, swelling of the face, lips, tongue, or throat. \n- Beta-blockers such as metoprolol and carvedilol may lower heart rate and cause fatigue. \n- Important interactions to check: duplicate blood pressure therapy, potassium supplements or potassium-sparing diuretics with ACE inhibitors/ARBs, NSAIDs with ACE inhibitors/ARBs, and other heart-rate-lowering medications with beta-blockers. \n \n7. Diuretics \n \nExamples: \n- Furosemide \n- Bumetanide \n- Torsemide \n- Hydrochlorothiazide \n- Spironolactone \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- Diuretics help remove extra fluid and may be used for heart failure, kidney disease, liver disease, or high blood pressure. \n- They may increase urination, especially shortly after a dose. \n- Side effects may include dizziness, dehydration, kidney changes, and electrolyte changes. \n- Loop and thiazide diuretics can lower potassium or magnesium. \n- Spironolactone can increase potassium. \n- Important interactions to check: ACE inhibitors, ARBs, ARNIs, potassium supplements, TMP-SMX, lithium, digoxin risk with electrolyte abnormalities, NSAIDs, nephrotoxins, and other medications affecting potassium or renal function. \n \n8. GI Protection and Acid Suppression \n \nExamples: \n- Pantoprazole \n- Omeprazole \n- Esomeprazole \n- Famotidine \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- These medications reduce stomach acid and may be used for reflux, ulcers, GI bleed prevention, or stress ulcer prophylaxis. \n- Review whether therapy is temporary or chronic. \n- Encourage reassessment of long-term use when appropriate. \n- Important interactions to check: acid suppression or antacids with medications affected by gastric pH or cations, including selected azoles, mycophenolate, oral iron, levothyroxine, doxycycline, and fluoroquinolones. \n \n9. Antiemetics and Nausea Medications \n \nExamples: \n- Ondansetron \n- Prochlorperazine \n- Promethazine \n- Metoclopramide \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- These medications help prevent or treat nausea and vomiting. \n- They may cause drowsiness, dizziness, constipation, or QT prolongation risk. \n- Metoclopramide can cause restlessness, tremor, stiffness, or abnormal movements; these may require prompt clinical evaluation. \n- Important interactions to check: QT-prolonging medications, serotonergic medications, dopamine blockers or antipsychotics, CNS depressants, and Parkinson disease medications. \n \n10. Bowel Regimen \n \nExamples: \n- Senna \n- Polyethylene glycol \n- Docusate \n- Bisacodyl \n- Lactulose \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- Bowel medications are commonly used with opioids, immobility, surgery, constipation, or liver disease. \n- Explain whether the medication softens stool, stimulates bowel movement, or draws water into the bowel. \n- Encourage fluids if appropriate for the patient\u0027s condition. \n- Lactulose may be used in liver disease to reduce confusion from hepatic encephalopathy; bowel movement goals should be reviewed. \n \n11. Psychiatric and Sleep Medications \n \nExamples: \n- Sertraline \n- Escitalopram \n- Quetiapine \n- Haloperidol \n- Trazodone \n- Melatonin \n- Lorazepam \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- Review the indication, such as depression, anxiety, sleep, agitation, delirium, or other psychiatric conditions. \n- Counsel on sedation, dizziness, falls, and avoiding alcohol. \n- Benzodiazepines such as lorazepam can cause dependence, confusion, falls, and respiratory depression, especially with opioids. \n- SSRIs may take several weeks for full effect when started for mood disorders. \n- Important interactions to check: opioids, alcohol, other CNS depressants, QT-prolonging medications, serotonergic combinations, MAOIs, linezolid, tramadol, and bleeding risk with anticoagulants or antiplatelets. \n \n12. Seizure Medications \n \nGeneral inpatient counseling points: \n- Many medications in this section can be used for seizures and for other conditions such as mood disorders, nerve pain, migraine prevention, or withdrawal protocols. Confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- If being used for seizures, these medications may help prevent seizures, treat active seizures, or reduce seizure recurrence after neurologic injury, surgery, withdrawal, or other high-risk conditions. \n- The pharmacist should check for drug-drug interactions, renal or hepatic dose adjustment, duplicate seizure therapy, route changes, and whether the patient was taking seizure medications before admission. \n- If seizure therapy will continue after discharge, the pharmacist should review adherence, missed-dose instructions, follow-up, and major interaction precautions. \n \nLevetiracetam \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure prevention or treatment; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy. If being used for seizures, this medication helps lower the chance of seizure activity. \n- Common side effects and significance: sleepiness or fatigue (very common; usually mild/manage but increases fall risk), dizziness (common to very common; clinically significant if unsafe ambulation), mood or behavior changes (common; clinically significant), worsening depression or suicidal thoughts (uncommon but potentially serious). \n- Approximate frequency: adult epilepsy trials report somnolence around 15%, asthenia/fatigue around 15%, and dizziness around 9%; psychiatric or behavioral symptoms vary by population and should be actively monitored. \n \nPhenytoin / Fosphenytoin \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure treatment or prevention; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy. If being used for seizures, this medication helps control seizure activity, and the team may check blood levels to keep the amount in a safe range. \n- Common side effects and significance: dizziness, drowsiness, unsteady walking, slurred speech, abnormal eye movements, nausea, and gum changes are clinically significant because they may signal toxicity or long-term adverse effects. \n- Approximate frequency: exact percentages vary and are not consistently presented as a single rate in labeling; treat neurologic toxicity symptoms as potentially serious, especially when levels are high or albumin is low. \n- Important interactions to check: tube feeds, warfarin, DOACs, antiplatelets, azole antifungals, amiodarone, antibiotics, transplant medications, hormonal contraceptives, and other antiepileptic drugs. \n \nValproate / Valproic Acid / Divalproex \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure control or another neurologic/psychiatric indication; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy, such as seizure control or a neurologic/mood-related treatment plan. \n- Common side effects and significance: nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, sleepiness, dizziness, tremor, and thrombocytopenia are common and may be clinically significant. Liver injury, pancreatitis, hyperammonemia, very low platelet count, and serious birth-defect risk are potentially serious. \n- Approximate frequency: labeling commonly reports several GI and CNS effects in the greater-than-5% range depending on indication; thrombocytopenia is dose- and concentration-related and should be followed with labs rather than counseling by percentage alone. \n- Important interactions to check: carbapenem antibiotics, lamotrigine, other antiepileptic drugs, anticoagulants, antiplatelets, aspirin, and other medications affecting bleeding, sedation, or liver risk. \n \nLacosamide \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure treatment or prevention; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy. If being used for seizures, this medication helps reduce seizure activity. \n- Common side effects and significance: dizziness, sleepiness, headache, nausea, double vision, blurred vision, vomiting, fatigue, and unsteady walking are usually mild/manage but clinically significant for fall risk. Fainting, heart rhythm changes, and serious allergic reactions are potentially serious. \n- Approximate frequency: pooled adult adjunctive-therapy trials reported dizziness about 23% to 25%, somnolence about 17%, headache about 14%, nausea about 10% to 11%, diplopia about 11%, and vomiting about 9%. \n- Important interactions to check: beta-blockers, calcium channel blockers, amiodarone, other PR-prolonging medications, and CNS depressants. \n \nCarbamazepine \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure treatment/prevention or another neurologic/psychiatric indication; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy, such as seizure prevention, nerve pain treatment, or a mood-related treatment plan. \n- Common side effects and significance: dizziness, drowsiness, nausea, vomiting, unsteady walking, low sodium, and rash are common to very common depending on dose and population. New, widespread, blistering, or severe rash, blood dyscrasias, liver injury, and symptomatic hyponatremia are potentially serious. \n- Approximate frequency: exact rates vary by formulation and study; use very common/common language unless the hospital reference provides a product-specific percentage. \n- Important interactions to check: anticoagulants, antiplatelets, azole antifungals, macrolides, antipsychotics, transplant medications, hormonal contraceptives, other antiepileptic drugs, and CYP3A inhibitors or inducers. \n \nOxcarbazepine \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure treatment/prevention or another neurologic/psychiatric indication; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy. If being used for seizures, this medication helps reduce seizure activity. \n- Common side effects and significance: dizziness, sleepiness, double vision, fatigue, nausea, vomiting, abnormal vision, headache, tremor, and unsteady walking are common to very common and clinically significant for fall risk. Low sodium and serious rash are potentially serious. \n- Approximate frequency: labeling identifies many adult and pediatric adverse reactions as at least 10% more frequent than comparator in some settings; discontinuation was associated with dizziness 6.4%, diplopia 5.9%, ataxia 5.2%, vomiting 5.1%, nausea 4.9%, somnolence 3.8%, rash 1.4%, and hyponatremia 1.0%. \n- Important interactions to check: diuretics or other hyponatremia-risk medications, hormonal contraceptives, other antiepileptic drugs, and CYP3A/CYP2C19 interaction risks. \n \nLamotrigine \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure treatment/prevention or mood-related therapy; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy, such as seizure prevention or mood stabilization. \n- Common side effects and significance: dizziness, headache, nausea, double vision, blurred vision, sleepiness, coordination problems, and rash are common to very common. Rash can be potentially serious because rare cases may progress to serious skin reactions. \n- Approximate frequency: adult epilepsy labeling reports common reactions at 5% or more; examples include dizziness, headache, nausea, somnolence, diplopia, ataxia, blurred vision, and rash. In one adult adjunctive-trial table, diplopia was 28%, ataxia 22%, and rash 10%. \n- Important interactions to check: valproate, carbamazepine, phenytoin, phenobarbital, primidone, rifampin, estrogen-containing products, and recent missed doses or restart timing. \n \nTopiramate \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure treatment/prevention or another neurologic indication; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy, such as seizure prevention or migraine prevention. \n- Common side effects and significance: sleepiness, dizziness, tingling, appetite decrease, weight loss, slowed thinking, word-finding trouble, memory difficulty, and vision changes are common and may be clinically significant. Acute eye pain/vision loss, metabolic acidosis, kidney stones, overheating, and suicidal thoughts are potentially serious. \n- Approximate frequency: adult epilepsy labeling commonly reports several CNS effects at 5% or more; discontinuation due to adverse reactions occurred in about 28% of adults exposed in epilepsy clinical studies. \n- Important interactions to check: CNS depressants, carbonic anhydrase inhibitors, valproate, lithium, metformin when acidosis risk is relevant, and hormonal contraceptives at higher doses. \n \nPhenobarbital \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure treatment/prevention, withdrawal protocol use, or continuation of home therapy; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy, such as seizure control or withdrawal symptom management. It may cause sleepiness. \n- Common side effects and significance: sleepiness, dizziness, impaired coordination, confusion, low blood pressure, and slowed breathing are clinically significant, especially with IV therapy or other sedatives. Respiratory depression, new, widespread, blistering, or severe rash, and excessive sedation are potentially serious. \n- Approximate frequency: exact percentages vary and are not reliably summarized as a single rate across indications; treat sedation and respiratory symptoms as clinically significant regardless of percentage. \n- Important interactions to check: opioids, benzodiazepines, alcohol, other CNS depressants, anticoagulants, antipsychotics, hormonal contraceptives, transplant medications, and other CYP-metabolized drugs. \n \nGabapentin \n- Possible inpatient use: seizure-related therapy, nerve pain, withdrawal protocol use, or continuation of home therapy; confirm the patient-specific indication before counseling. \n- What to explain to the patient: Explain the chart-confirmed reason for therapy, such as nerve pain, seizure-related therapy, or withdrawal protocol use. \n- Common side effects and significance: dizziness, sleepiness, fatigue, swelling, and trouble walking are common and clinically significant for fall risk. Respiratory depression is potentially serious when combined with opioids, benzodiazepines, or other sedatives. \n- Approximate frequency: dizziness and somnolence are commonly reported in the greater-than-10% range in labeling for several indications; exact rates depend on indication and dose. \n- Important interactions to check: opioids, benzodiazepines, sleep medications, alcohol, other CNS depressants, and aluminum/magnesium antacids that may reduce gabapentin absorption (separate by 2 hours). \n \n13. Electrolytes and Supplements \n \nExamples: \n- Potassium chloride \n- Magnesium oxide \n- Phosphate supplements \n- Ferrous sulfate \n- Vitamin D \n- Thiamine \n- Folic acid \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- Explain why the supplement or replacement is needed. \n- Iron may darken stool and cause constipation. \n- Magnesium may cause diarrhea. \n- If supplements continue at discharge, review interactions and administration details at that time. \n- Important interactions to check: oral iron, calcium, magnesium, zinc, phosphate binders, antacids, and multivitamins with medications affected by cations, including doxycycline, fluoroquinolones, levothyroxine, and selected transplant or thyroid medications. \n \n14. Medications for Alcohol Withdrawal or Substance Use \n \nExamples: \n- Lorazepam \n- Diazepam \n- Phenobarbital \n- Thiamine \n- Folic acid \n- Multivitamins \n- Buprenorphine \n- Methadone \n- Naltrexone \n \nBasic counseling points: \n- Explain whether the medication is for withdrawal treatment, vitamin replacement, craving reduction, or opioid use disorder. \n- Sedating medications can increase fall risk and should not be combined with alcohol or other sedatives unless directed. \n- Buprenorphine and methadone require coordination with outpatient follow-up if continued after discharge. \n- Review overdose prevention, naloxone access, and follow-up care when appropriate. \n- Thiamine and folic acid may be used to prevent or treat vitamin deficiencies. \n- Important interactions to check: opioids, benzodiazepines, phenobarbital, alcohol, other CNS depressants, QT-prolonging medications with methadone, and opioid antagonists or partial agonists when transitioning therapy. "};
